# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gallium-nitride
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] An **active electronically scanned array** (**AESA**) is a type of phased array antenna, which is a computer-controlled antenna array in which the beam of radio waves can be electronically steered to point in different directions without moving the antenna.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] In the AESA, each antenna element is connected to a small solid-state transmit/receive module (TRM) under the control of a computer, which performs the functions of a transmitter and/or receiver for the antenna.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] This contrasts with a passive electronically scanned array (PESA), in which all the antenna elements are connected to a single transmitter and/or receiver through phase shifters under the control of the computer.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] AESA's main use is in radar and these are known as active phased-array radar (APAR).
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] The AESA is a more advanced, sophisticated, second-generation of the original PESA phased-array technology.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] PESAs can only emit a single beam of radio waves at a single frequency at a time.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] The PESA must utilize a Butler matrix if multiple beams are required.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] The AESA can radiate multiple beams of radio waves at multiple frequencies simultaneously.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] AESA radars can spread their signal emissions across a wider range of frequencies, which makes them more difficult to detect over background noise, allowing ships and aircraft to radiate powerful radar signals while still remaining stealthy, as well as being more resistant to jamming.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Hybrids of AESA and PESA can also be found consisting of subarrays that individually resemble PESAs, where each subarray has its own RF front end.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Using a hybrid approach, the benefits of AESA (e.g., multiple independent beams) can be realized at a lower cost compared to pure AESA.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] The first ground-based, ship-based and airborne AESA radars became operational in the mid 1990s.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Bell Labs proposed replacing the Nike Zeus radars with a phased-array system in 1960, and was given the go-ahead for development in June 1961.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] The result was the Zeus Multi-function Array Radar (ZMAR), an early example of an active electronically steered array radar system.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] ZMAR became MAR when the Zeus program ended in favor of the Nike-X system in 1963.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] The MAR (Multi-function Array Radar) was made of a large number of small antennas, each one connected to a separate computer-controlled transmitter or receiver.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Using a variety of beamforming and signal processing steps, a single MAR was able to perform long-distance detection, track generation, discrimination of warheads from decoys, and tracking of the outbound interceptor missiles.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] MAR allowed the entire battle over a wide space to be controlled from a single site.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Each MAR, and its associated battle center, would process tracks for hundreds of targets.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] The system would then select the most appropriate battery for each one, and hand off particular targets for them to attack.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] One battery would normally be associated with the MAR, while others would be distributed around it.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Remote batteries were equipped with a much simpler radar whose primary purpose was to track the outgoing Sprint missiles before they became visible to the potentially distant MAR.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] These smaller Missile Site Radars (MSR) were passively scanned, forming only a single beam instead of the MAR's multiple beams.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] While MAR was ultimately successful, the cost of the system was enormous.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] When the ABM problem became so complex that even a system like MAR could no longer deal with realistic attack scenarios, the Nike-X concept was abandoned in favor of much simpler concepts like the Sentinel program, which did not use MAR.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] A second example, MAR-II, was abandoned in-place on Kwajalein Atoll.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] The first Soviet APAR, the 5N65, was developed in 1963–1965 as a part of the S-225 ABM system.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] After some modifications in the system concept in 1967 it was built at Sary Shagan Test Range in 1970–1971 and nicknamed Flat Twin in the West.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Four years later another radar of this design was built on Kura Test Range, while the S-225 system was never commissioned.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] US based manufacturers of the AESA radars used in the F-22 and Super Hornet include Northrop Grumman and Raytheon.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] These companies also design, develop and manufacture the transmit/receive modules which comprise the 'building blocks' of an AESA radar.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] The requisite electronics technology was developed in-house via Department of Defense research programs such as MMIC Program.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] In 2016 the Congress funded a military industry competition to produce new radars for two dozen National Guard fighter aircraft.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Radar systems generally work by connecting an antenna to a powerful radio transmitter to emit a short pulse of signal.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] The transmitter is then disconnected and the antenna is connected to a sensitive receiver which amplifies any echos from target objects.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] By measuring the time it takes for the signal to return, the radar receiver can determine the distance to the object.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] The receiver then sends the resulting output to a display of some sort.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] The transmitter elements were typically klystron tubes or magnetrons, which are suitable for amplifying or generating a narrow range of frequencies to high power levels.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] To scan a portion of the sky, the radar antenna must be physically moved to point in different directions.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Starting in the 1960s new solid-state devices capable of delaying the transmitter signal in a controlled way were introduced.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] That led to the first practical large-scale passive electronically scanned array (PESA), or simply phased-array radar.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] PESAs took a signal from a single source, split it into hundreds of paths, selectively delayed some of them, and sent them to individual antennas.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] The radio signals from the separate antennas overlapped in space, and the interference patterns between the individual signals were controlled to reinforce the signal in certain directions, and mute it in all others.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] The delays could be easily controlled electronically, allowing the beam to be steered very quickly without moving the antenna.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] A PESA can scan a volume of space much quicker than a traditional mechanical system.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Additionally, thanks to progress in electronics, PESAs added the ability to produce several active beams, allowing them to continue scanning the sky while at the same time focusing smaller beams on certain targets for tracking or guiding semi-active radar homing missiles.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] PESAs quickly became widespread on ships and large fixed emplacements in the 1960s, followed by airborne sensors as the electronics shrank.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] AESAs are the result of further developments in solid-state electronics.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] In earlier systems the transmitted signal was originally created in a klystron or traveling wave tube or similar device, which are relatively large.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Receiver electronics were also large due to the high frequencies that they worked with.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] The introduction of gallium arsenide microelectronics through the 1980s served to greatly reduce the size of the receiver elements until effective ones could be built at sizes similar to those of handheld radios, only a few cubic centimeters in volume.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] The introduction of JFETs and MESFETs did the same to the transmitter side of the systems as well.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] It gave rise to amplifier-transmitters with a low-power solid-state waveform generator feeding an amplifier, allowing any radar so equipped to transmit on a much wider range of frequencies, to the point of changing operating frequency with every pulse sent out.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Shrinking the entire assembly (the transmitter, receiver and antenna) into a single "transmitter-receiver module" (TRM) about the size of a carton of milk and arraying these elements produces an AESA.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] The primary advantage of an AESA over a PESA is the capability of the different modules to operate on different frequencies.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Unlike the PESA, where the signal is generated at single frequencies by a small number of transmitters, in the AESA each module generates and radiates its own independent signal.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] This allows the AESA to produce numerous simultaneous "sub-beams" that it can recognize due to different frequencies, and actively track a much larger number of targets.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] AESAs can also produce beams that consist of many different frequencies at once, using post-processing of the combined signal from a number of TRMs to re-create a display as if there was a single powerful beam being sent.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] However, this means that the noise present in each frequency is also received and added.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] AESAs add many capabilities of their own to those of the PESAs.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Among these are: the ability to form multiple beams simultaneously, to use groups of TRMs for different roles concurrently, like radar detection, and, more importantly, their multiple simultaneous beams and scanning frequencies create difficulties for traditional, correlation-type radar detectors.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Radar systems work by sending out a signal and then listening for its echo off distant objects.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Each of these paths, to and from the target, is subject to the inverse square law of propagation in both the transmitted signal and the signal reflected back.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] That means that a radar's received energy drops with the fourth power of the distance, which is why radar systems require high powers, often in the megawatt range, to be effective at long range.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] The radar signal being sent out is a simple radio signal, and can be received with a simple radio receiver.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Military aircraft and ships have defensive receivers, called "radar warning receivers" (RWR), which detect when an enemy radar beam is on them, thus revealing the position of the enemy.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Unlike the radar unit, which must send the pulse out and then receive its reflection, the target's receiver does not need the reflection and thus the signal drops off only as the square of distance.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] This means that the receiver is always at an advantage [neglecting disparity in antenna size] over the radar in terms of range – it will always be able to detect the signal long before the radar can see the target's echo.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Since the position of the radar is extremely useful information in an attack on that platform, this means that radars generally must be turned off for lengthy periods if they are subject to attack; this is common on ships, for instance.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Unlike the radar, which knows which direction it is sending its signal, the receiver simply gets a pulse of energy and has to interpret it.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Since the radio spectrum is filled with noise, the receiver's signal is integrated over a short period of time, making periodic sources like a radar add up and stand out over the random background.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] The rough direction can be calculated using a rotating antenna, or similar passive array using phase or amplitude comparison.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Typically RWRs store the detected pulses for a short period of time, and compare their broadcast frequency and pulse repetition frequency against a database of known radars.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] The direction to the source is normally combined with symbology indicating the likely purpose of the radar – airborne early warning and control, surface-to-air missile, etc.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] This technique is much less useful against a radar with a frequency-agile (solid state) transmitter.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Since the AESA (or PESA) can change its frequency with every pulse (except when using doppler filtering), and generally does so using a random sequence, integrating over time does not help pull the signal out of the background noise.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Moreover, a radar may be designed to extend the duration of the pulse and lower its peak power.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] An AESA or modern PESA will often have the capability to alter these parameters during operation.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] This makes no difference to the total energy reflected by the target but makes the detection of the pulse by an RWR system less likely.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Nor does the AESA have any sort of fixed pulse repetition frequency, which can also be varied and thus hide any periodic brightening across the entire spectrum.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Older generation RWRs are essentially useless against AESA radars, which is why AESAs are also known as *low probability of intercept radars*.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Modern RWRs must be made highly sensitive (small angles and bandwidths for individual antennas, low transmission loss and noise) and add successive pulses through time-frequency processing to achieve useful detection rates.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Jamming is likewise much more difficult against an AESA.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Traditionally, jammers have operated by determining the operating frequency of the radar and then broadcasting a signal on it to confuse the receiver as to which is the "real" pulse and which is the jammer's.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] This technique works as long as the radar system cannot easily change its operating frequency.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] When the transmitters were based on klystron tubes this was generally true, and radars, especially airborne ones, had only a few frequencies to choose among.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] A jammer could listen to those possible frequencies and select the one to be used to jam.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Most radars using modern electronics are capable of changing their operating frequency with every pulse.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] This can make jamming less effective; although it is possible to send out broadband white noise to conduct barrage jamming against all the possible frequencies, this reduces the amount of jammer energy in any one frequency.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] An AESA has the additional capability of emitting a single broad-spectrum pulse, called a chirp, which is more difficult to jam.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] AESAs can also be switched to a receive-only mode, and use these powerful jamming signals to track its source, something that required a separate receiver in older platforms.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] By integrating received signals from the targets' own radar along with a lower rate of data from its own broadcasts, a detection system with a precise RWR like an AESA can generate more data with less energy.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Some receive beamforming-capable systems, usually ground-based, may even discard a transmitter entirely.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] However, using a single receiving antenna only gives a direction.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Obtaining a range and a target vector requires at least two physically separate passive devices for triangulation to provide instantaneous determinations, unless phase interferometry is used.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Target motion analysis can estimate these quantities by incorporating many directional measurements over time, along with knowledge of the position of the receiver and constraints on the possible motion of the target.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Since each element in an AESA is a powerful radio receiver, active arrays have many roles besides traditional radar.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] One use is to dedicate several of the elements to reception of common radar signals, eliminating the need for a separate radar warning receiver.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] The same basic concept can be used to provide traditional radio support, and with some elements also broadcasting, form a very high bandwidth data link.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] The F-35 uses this mechanism to send sensor data between aircraft in order to provide a synthetic picture of higher resolution and range than any one radar could generate.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] AESAs are also much more reliable than either PESAs or older designs.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Since each module operates independently of the others, single failures have little effect on the operation of the system as a whole.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] Additionally, the modules individually operate at low powers, perhaps 40 to 60 watts, so the need for a large high-voltage power supply is eliminated.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] With a half wavelength distance between the elements, the maximum beam angle is approximately $\pm 45$ °.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] With a shorter element distance, the highest field of view (FOV) for a flat phased-array antenna is currently 120° ( $\pm 60$ °), although this can be combined with mechanical steering as noted above.
[src:gallium-nitride/active-electronically-scanned-array] The first AESA radar employed on an operational warship was the Japanese OPS-24 manufactured by Mitsubishi Electric introduced on the JDS *Hamagiri* (DD-155), the first ship of the latter batch of the *Asagiri*-class destroyer, launched in 1988.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] The **AN/TPS-80 Ground/Air Task Oriented Radar** (G/ATOR) is the United States Marine Corps next-generation Air Surveillance/Air Defense and Air Traffic Control (ATC) Radar.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] The mobile active electronically scanned array radar system is being developed and produced by Northrop Grumman and was expected to reach initial operating capability in August 2016.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] Initial production began in June of 2019.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] In October of 2025, one unit was controversially deployed to the Island nation of Trinidad and Tobago, which is just 7 miles off the coast of Venezuela.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] In accordance with the Joint Electronics Type Designation System (JETDS), the "*AN/TPS-80*" designation represents the 80th design of an Army-Navy electronic device for ground transportable search radar system.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] The JETDS system also now is used to name all Department of Defense electronic systems.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] The Ground/Air Task Oriented Radar (G/ATOR) is a single material solution for the mobile Multi-Role Radar System and Ground Weapons Locating Radar (GWLR) requirements.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] It is a three-dimensional, medium/long-range multi-role radar designed to detect unmanned aerial systems, cruise missiles, air-breathing targets, rockets, artillery, and mortars.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] G/ATOR is designed to fulfil expeditionary needs across the Marine Air-Ground Task Force spectrum, replacing five legacy radar systems with a single solution.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] The five Marine Corps legacy radar systems being replaced by this multi-function capability include: the AN/TPS-63 (air defense), AN/TPS-73 (air-traffic control), AN/MPQ-62 (short-range air defense), AN/TPQ-46 (counter-fire target acquisition) and UPS-3 (target tracking).
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] Additionally, it will augment the AN/TPS-59 long-range radar.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] The Program Executive Office (PEO), Land Systems Marine Corps is executing the G/ATOR program, as an evolutionary acquisition program of four capabilities, referred to as blocks.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] G/ATOR provides real-time radar measurement data to the Tactical Air Operations Module, Common Aviation Command and Control System (CAC2S), Composite Tracking Network, and Advanced Field Artillery Tactical Data System.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] Development of the G/ATOR began in September 2005 when the Marine Corps awarded a $7.9 million contract to Northrop Grumman Electronic Systems.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] Initial design requirements required planning for short-range air surveillance, counter-battery fire and target acquisition, and sensor networking.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] The requirement required Block 1 to allow for incremental implementation of the following blocks without equipment or software redesign.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] In 2009, a $14 million cost overrun for the G/ATOR, was attributed to requirements creep and the increasing cost of scarce materials required in advanced electronic components.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] In 2012 the Marine Corps and Northrop Grumman began Block 2 development, beginning with upgrading the Block 1 equipment and software for performing GWLR requirements.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] The G/ATOR program obtained a successful Milestone C decision in March 2014.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] In October 2014, a 207.3 million dollar low rate initial production (LRIP) contract was awarded to Northrop Grumman for the first four systems.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] In March 2015, another contract worth $113 million was awarded to produce two additional systems to be delivered in October 2017.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] In September 2015, the Marine Corps awarded Northrop Grumman a $58.7 million contract to incorporate and test the GWLR mode for the G/ATOR.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] In September 2016, the Marine Corps awarded Northrop Grumman a $375 million contract for nine additional LRIP systems that will incorporate gallium nitride (GaN) technology.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] In June 2019, the Marine Corps awarded Northrop Grumman a $958 million contract for full-rate production of 30 GaN G/ATOR Systems.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] A total of 60 G/ATOR systems are planned for procurement through 2029.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] In December 2019, the Marine Corps awarded Northrop Grumman a $188 million contract, for the firm-fixed-price portion of a previously awarded contract (M67854-19-C-0043).
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] This modification is for the purchase of six Gallium Nitride full-rate-production systems and associated travel in support of Program Executive Officer Land Systems, Quantico, Virginia.
[src:gallium-nitride/air-task-oriented-radar] Saab is subcontracted by Northrop Grumman Corporation and has delivered major subsystems and assemblies as well as software since Lot1 and has been part of the development since originally contracted in 2007.
[src:gallium-nitride/alp-300-g] ALP 300-G was designed as an early warning radar system.
[src:gallium-nitride/alp-300-g] The ALP 300-G radar has the ability to receive over 4 thousand transmissions.
[src:gallium-nitride/alp-300-g] Aselsan CEO said in a statement that "the radar system can make nearly 500 digital communications and has the ability to process the content of 81 DVDs per second.
[src:gallium-nitride/alp-300-g] More than 435 thousand lines of code were used in the radar.
[src:gallium-nitride/alp-300-g] We have nearly 20 patents in the development of this radar.
[src:gallium-nitride/alp-300-g] Our AL 300-G Mobile Radar can also be installed in 30 minutes.
[src:gallium-nitride/alp-300-g] The Turkish Ministry of Defense ordered the ALP 300-G radar worth $225 million from Aselsan in December 2024.
[src:gallium-nitride/alp-300-g] Deliveries are planned to be made between 2026 and 2031.
[src:gallium-nitride/alp-300-g] On 27 August 2025, at a ceremony attended by President Erdoğan, air defense systems worth approximately $460 million, including the ALP 300-G and ALP 100-G, were delivered to the Turkish Armed Forces.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:gallium-nitride/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Its sensitivity to ionizing radiation is low (like other group III nitrides), making it a suitable material for solar cell arrays for satellites.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Military and space applications could also benefit as devices have shown stability in high-radiation environments.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Because GaN transistors can operate at much higher temperatures and work at much higher voltages than gallium arsenide (GaAs) transistors, they make ideal power amplifiers at microwave frequencies.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] In addition, GaN offers promising characteristics for THz devices.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Due to high power density and voltage breakdown limits GaN is also emerging as a promising candidate for 5G cellular base station applications.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] GaN is a very hard (Knoop hardness 14.21 GPa), mechanically stable wide-bandgap semiconductor material with high heat capacity and thermal conductivity.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] In its pure form it resists cracking and can be deposited in thin film on sapphire or silicon carbide, despite the mismatch in their lattice constants.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] GaN can be doped with silicon (Si) or with oxygen to n-type and with magnesium (Mg) to p-type.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] However, the Si and Mg atoms change the way the GaN crystals grow, introducing tensile stresses and making them brittle.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Gallium nitride compounds also tend to have a high dislocation density, on the order of 108 to 1010 defects per square centimeter.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Army Research Laboratory (ARL) provided the first measurement of the high field electron velocity in GaN in 1999.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Scientists at ARL experimentally obtained a peak steady-state velocity of 1.9×107 cm/s, with a transit time of 2.5 picoseconds, attained at an electric field of 225 kV/cm.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] With this information, the electron mobility was calculated, thus providing data for the design of GaN devices.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] One of the earliest syntheses of gallium nitride was at the George Herbert Jones Laboratory in 1932.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] An early synthesis of gallium nitride was by Robert Juza and Harry Hahn in 1938.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] GaN with a high crystalline quality can be obtained by depositing a buffer layer at low temperatures.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Such high-quality GaN led to the discovery of p-type GaN, p–n junction blue/UV-LEDs and room-temperature stimulated emission (essential for laser action).
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] This has led to the commercialization of high-performance blue LEDs and long-lifetime violet laser diodes, and to the development of nitride-based devices such as UV detectors and high-speed field-effect transistors.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] High-brightness GaN light-emitting diodes (LEDs) completed the range of primary colors, and made possible applications such as daylight-visible full-color LED displays, white LEDs and blue laser devices.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] The first GaN-based high-brightness LEDs used a thin film of GaN deposited via metalorganic vapour-phase epitaxy (MOVPE) on sapphire.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Other substrates used are zinc oxide, with lattice constant mismatch of only 2% and silicon carbide (SiC).
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Group III nitride semiconductors are, in general, recognized as one of the most promising semiconductor families for fabricating optical devices in the visible short-wavelength and UV region.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] The very high breakdown voltages, high electron mobility, and high saturation velocity of GaN has made it an ideal candidate for high-power and high-temperature microwave applications, as evidenced by its high Johnson's figure of merit.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Potential markets for high-power/high-frequency devices based on GaN include microwave radio-frequency power amplifiers (e.g., those used in high-speed wireless data transmission) and high-voltage switching devices for power grids.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] A potential mass-market application for GaN-based RF transistors is as the microwave source for microwave ovens, replacing the magnetrons currently used.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] The large band gap means that the performance of GaN transistors is maintained up to higher temperatures (~400 °C) than silicon transistors (~150 °C) because it lessens the effects of thermal generation of charge carriers that are inherent to any semiconductor.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] The first gallium nitride metal semiconductor field-effect transistors (GaN MESFET) were experimentally demonstrated in 1993 and they are being actively developed.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] In 2010, the first enhancement-mode GaN transistors became generally available.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Only n-channel transistors were available.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] These devices were designed to replace power MOSFETs in applications where switching speed or power conversion efficiency is critical.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] These transistors are built by growing a thin layer of GaN on top of a standard silicon wafer, often referred to as *GaN-on-Si* by manufacturers.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] This allows the FETs to maintain costs similar to silicon power MOSFETs but with the superior electrical performance of GaN, and consists of growing GaN on silicon wafers using MOCVD Epitaxy.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Another seemingly viable solution for realizing enhancement-mode GaN-channel HFETs is to employ a lattice-matched quaternary AlInGaN layer of acceptably low spontaneous polarization mismatch to GaN.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] For power applications, GaN HEMTs are available with a range of different levels of integration, including discrete, cascode, ICeGaN and integrated gate drive.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] GaN ICs monolithically integrate a GaN FET, GaN-based drive circuitry and circuit protection into a single surface-mount device.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Integration means that the gate-drive loop has essentially zero impedance, which further improves efficiency by virtually eliminating FET turn-off losses.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Academic studies into creating low-voltage GaN power ICs began at the Hong Kong University of Science and Technology (HKUST) and the first devices were demonstrated in 2015.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Commercial GaN power IC production began in 2018.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] In 2016 the first GaN CMOS logic using PMOS and NMOS transistors was reported with gate lengths of 0.5 μm (gate widths of the PMOS and NMOS transistors were 500 μm and 50 μm, respectively).
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] GaN-based violet laser diodes are used to read Blu-ray Discs.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] The mixture of GaN with In (InGaN) or Al (AlGaN) with a band gap dependent on the ratio of In or Al to Ga allows the manufacture of light-emitting diodes (LEDs) with colors that can go from red to ultra-violet.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] GaN transistors are suitable for high frequency, high voltage, high temperature and high-efficiency applications.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] GaN is efficient at transferring current, and this ultimately means that less energy is lost to heat.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] GaN high-electron-mobility transistors (HEMT) have been offered commercially since 2006, and have found immediate use in various wireless infrastructure applications due to their high efficiency and high voltage operation.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] A second generation of devices with shorter gate lengths will address higher-frequency telecom and aerospace applications.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] GaN-based metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistors (MOSFET) and metal–semiconductor field-effect transistors (MESFET) also offer advantages including lower loss in high power electronics, especially in automotive and electric car applications.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Since 2008 these can be formed on a silicon substrate.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] High-voltage (800 V) Schottky barrier diodes (SBDs) have also been made.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] The higher efficiency and high power density of integrated GaN power management ICs allows them to reduce the size, weight and component count of applications including mobile and laptop chargers, consumer electronics, computing equipment and electric vehicles.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] GaN-based electronics (not pure GaN) have the potential to substantially cut energy consumption, not only in consumer applications but even for power transmission utilities.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Unlike silicon transistors that switch off due to power surges, GaN transistors are typically depletion mode devices (i.e. on / resistive when the gate-source voltage is zero).
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] GaN technology is also utilized in military electronics such as active electronically scanned array radars.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Thales Group introduced the Ground Master 400 radar in 2010 utilizing GaN technology.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] In 2021 Thales put in operation more than 50,000 GaN Transmitters on radar systems.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Army funded Lockheed Martin to incorporate GaN active-device technology into the AN/TPQ-53 radar system to replace two medium-range radar systems, the AN/TPQ-36 and the AN/TPQ-37.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] The AN/TPQ-53 radar system was designed to detect, classify, track, and locate enemy indirect fire systems, as well as unmanned aerial systems.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] The AN/TPQ-53 radar system provided enhanced performance, greater mobility, increased reliability and supportability, lower life-cycle cost, and reduced crew size compared to the AN/TPQ-36 and the AN/TPQ-37 systems.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Lockheed Martin fielded other tactical operational radars with GaN technology in 2018, including TPS-77 Multi Role Radar System deployed to Latvia and Romania.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] In 2019, Lockheed Martin's partner ELTA Systems Limited, developed a GaN-based ELM-2084 Multi Mission Radar that was able to detect and track air craft and ballistic targets, while providing fire control guidance for missile interception or air defense artillery.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] On April 8, 2020, Saab flight tested its new GaN designed AESA X-band radar in a JAS-39 Gripen fighter.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Saab already offers products with GaN based radars, like the Giraffe radar, Erieye, GlobalEye, and Arexis EW.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] India's Defence Research and Development Organisation is developing Virupaakhsha radar for Sukhoi Su-30MKI based on GaN technology.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] The radar is a further development of Uttam AESA Radar for use on HAL Tejas which employs GaAs technology.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Turkish Aselsan company delivered the first GaN-based Turkish AESA radar, ALP 300-G, to the Turkish Armed Forces in May 2024.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] GaN nanotubes and nanowires are proposed for applications in nanoscale electronics, optoelectronics and biochemical-sensing applications.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] When doped with a suitable transition metal such as manganese, GaN is a promising spintronics material (magnetic semiconductors).
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] GaN crystals can be grown from a molten Na/Ga melt held under 100 atmospheres of pressure of N2 at 750 °C.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Gallium nitride can also be synthesized by injecting ammonia gas into molten gallium at 900–980 °C at normal atmospheric pressure.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Blue, white and ultraviolet LEDs are grown on industrial scale by metalorganic vapour-phase epitaxy (MOVPE).
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] The precursors are ammonia with either trimethylgallium or triethylgallium, the carrier gas being nitrogen or hydrogen.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Growth temperature ranges between 800 and 1100 °C.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Introduction of trimethylaluminium and/or trimethylindium is necessary for growing quantum wells and other kinds of heterostructures.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Commercially, GaN crystals can be grown using molecular beam epitaxy or MBE.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] MBE growth of GaN can be divided into two categories, including ammonia-MBE (NH3-MBE) and plasma assisted MBE (PA-MBE).
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] In NH3-MBE, NH3 is used as the nitrogen source, while a nitrogen RF plasma is used in PA-MBE.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] This process can be further modified to reduce dislocation densities.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] First, an ion beam is applied to the growth surface in order to create nanoscale roughness.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Polishing methods typically employ a liquid electrolyte and UV irradiation to enable mechanical removal of a thin oxide layer from the wafer.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] More recent methods have been developed that utilize solid-state polymer electrolytes that are solvent-free and require no radiation before polishing.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] GaN dust is an irritant to skin, eyes and lungs.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] The environment, health and safety aspects of gallium nitride sources (such as trimethylgallium and ammonia) and industrial hygiene monitoring studies of MOVPE sources have been reported in a 2004 review.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Bulk GaN is non-toxic and biocompatible.
[src:gallium-nitride/gallium-nitride] Therefore, it may be used in the electrodes and electronics of implants in living organisms.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-36-firefinder-radar] In accordance with the Joint Electronics Type Designation System (JETDS), the "*AN/TPQ-36*" designation represents the 36th design of an Army-Navy electronic device for ground transportable special combination radar system.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-36-firefinder-radar] Engineering development of the TPQ-36 began October 1973.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-36-firefinder-radar] Although full scale production was approved in December 1977, the system did not achieve full scale production until August 1978.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-36-firefinder-radar] Low rate initial production (LRIP) began in December 1976 ending in February 1981.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-36-firefinder-radar] Total crew size required for missions and operational requirements for extended periods was initially estimated at 8 personnel.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-36-firefinder-radar] The AN/TPQ-36(V)7 upgrade to the Firefinder added a Modular Azimuth Position System (MAPS).
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-36-firefinder-radar] MAPS has a north seeking laser gyrocompass and a microprocessor controlled Honeywell H-726 inertial navigation system.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-36-firefinder-radar] Prior Firefinder systems used a survey team to find site latitude, longitude, and direction to North.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-36-firefinder-radar] With MAPS, reaction time was limited only by the time taken to set up the site, since system geo-position was pre-loaded before sortie deployment.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-36-firefinder-radar] Firefinder (V)8 extended system performance, improved operator survivability and lowered life cycle cost.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-36-firefinder-radar] Greater processing power and the addition of a low noise amplifier to the radar antenna improved detection range by up to 50% and performance accuracy against certain threats.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-36-firefinder-radar] The AN/TPQ-36 is a passive electronically scanned array (PESA) electronically steered radar, meaning the radar antenna does not actually move while in operation.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-36-firefinder-radar] The radar antenna may however be moved manually if required.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-36-firefinder-radar] The system may also be operated in a friendly fire mode to determine the accuracy of counterbattery return fire, or for conducting radar registration or mean point of impact calibrations for friendly artillery.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-36-firefinder-radar] It can simultaneously locate up to 10 weapons including mortars, artillery, and rocket launchers, on first round and perform high-burst, datum-plane, and impact registrations.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-36-firefinder-radar] It can be used to adjust friendly fire, interfaces with tactical fire and predicts the impact of hostile projectiles.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-36-firefinder-radar] Its maximum range is 15 miles (24 km) with an effective range of 11 miles (18 km) for artillery and 15 miles (24 km) for rockets.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-36-firefinder-radar] It operates in the X-band at 32 frequencies.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-36-firefinder-radar] It features permanent storage for 99 targets, has a field exercise mode and uses a digital data interface.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-36-firefinder-radar] Northrop Grumman manufactures the AN/TPQ-36(V)8 Firefinder radar.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-36-firefinder-radar] Before its acquisition by Raytheon, the Hughes Aircraft Co. developed the TPQ-36 Firefinder radar at its facility at Fullerton, California, and manufactured it at its plant in Forest, Mississippi.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-37-firefinder-radar] Twelve of the radar systems had been delivered to the Indian Army by 2007 under a deal signed in 2002 as a cost of around $200 million.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-37-firefinder-radar] Carrier vehicles and support systems were supplied by Bharat Earth Movers Limited (now, BEML).
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-37-firefinder-radar] In accordance with the Joint Electronics Type Designation System (JETDS), the "*AN/TPQ-37*" designation represents the 37th design of an Army-Navy electronic device for ground transportable special combination radar system.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-37-firefinder-radar] The AN/TPQ-37 is an electronically steered radar, meaning the radar does not actually move while in operation.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-37-firefinder-radar] The radar scans a 90-degree sector for incoming rocket, artillery and mortar fire.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-37-firefinder-radar] Upon detecting a possible incoming round, the system verifies the contact before initiating a track sequence, continuing to search for new targets.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-37-firefinder-radar] The incoming round/rocket is tracked during its initial upward/launch trajectory (i.e., the linear portion of its flight path) prior to reaching apogee.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-37-firefinder-radar] A computer program analyzes the track data and then extrapolates the round's point of origin.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-37-firefinder-radar] This calculated point of origin is then reported to the operator with map coordinates, thus allowing friendly artillery to direct counter-battery fire towards the enemy artillery.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-37-firefinder-radar] The system has a reported range of up to 31 miles (50 km).
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-37-firefinder-radar] The system may also be operated in a friendly fire mode to determine the accuracy of counterbattery return fire.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-37-firefinder-radar] Before acquisition by Raytheon, the Hughes Aircraft Co. developed the AN/TPQ-37 Firefinder radar at its facility in Fullerton, California, and manufactures it at its plant in Forest, Mississippi.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-53-quick-reaction-capability-radar] In accordance with the Joint Electronics Type Designation System (JETDS), the "*AN/TPQ-53*" designation represents the 53rd design of an Army-Navy electronic device for ground transportable special combination radar system.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-53-quick-reaction-capability-radar] The TPQ-53 radar's delivery on 2 July 2009 followed its successful live-fire performance testing against indirect fire from mortars, artillery and rockets from a simulated enemy.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-53-quick-reaction-capability-radar] The system has been tested and approved by the US Army.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-53-quick-reaction-capability-radar] TPQ-53 radar systems will replace the aging AN/TPQ-36 and AN/TPQ-37 medium-range radars now in the Army's inventory.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-53-quick-reaction-capability-radar] Prior to September 2011, the system was known as "EQ-36 Counterfire Target Acquisition Radar".
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-53-quick-reaction-capability-radar] EQ-36 was a Lockheed reference to the “Enhanced AN/TPQ-36", their program to develop what eventually became the AN/TPQ-53.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-53-quick-reaction-capability-radar] In June 2013, the United States Army exercised a contract option to finish out the total production of 51 systems.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-53-quick-reaction-capability-radar] After a contract award 24 April 2017 has completed production, the Army will hold more than 170 such systems.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-53-quick-reaction-capability-radar] In April 2020, the first TPQ-53s with Gallium nitride (GaN) transmit-receive modules were delivered providing additional power, reliability and the possibility for extended range, and counterfire target acquisition (CTA).
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-53-quick-reaction-capability-radar] After Russian-backed separatists started operating tanks in Eastern Ukraine, the U.S. started sending military items to Ukraine, including twenty AN/TPQ-53 radar systems in 2015.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-53-quick-reaction-capability-radar] As a result, Ukraine's units thus equipped saw casualty rates decline from 47 percent to around 18 percent.
[src:gallium-nitride/tpq-53-quick-reaction-capability-radar] Ukrainian combat expertise with the system led to their providing training to U.S. forces.
